{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608953"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16053"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16053"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.07,0.2,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8744"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8744"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49144"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5753"},{"type":"tags","id":"8124"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20910"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMedications are classified into different risk categories based on their potential to cause harm during pregnancy. These categories help guide prescribing decisions for women who are pregnant or may become pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pregnancy medication categories describes drugs that have clear evidence of causing permanent fetal damage and are absolutely contraindicated during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Category B1 medications","Category B3 medications","Category C medications","Category D medications","Category X medications"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian pregnancy medication categories classify drugs based on their known or potential risks to the developing fetus:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory B1 medications\u003C/strong\u003E have been taken by only a limited number of pregnant women with no increase in malformation frequency\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory B3 medications\u003C/strong\u003E have been taken by a limited number of pregnant women with no direct or indirect harmful effects on the fetus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory C medications\u003C/strong\u003E may cause harmful effects on the fetus without causing malformations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory D medications\u003C/strong\u003E have caused or are suspected of causing increased fetal malformations or damage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory X medications\u003C/strong\u003E have such a high risk of causing permanent fetal damage that they should not be used in pregnancy or when pregnancy is possible\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of Category X medications include isotretinoin, thalidomide, and warfarin. The risk of fetal harm is considered to clearly outweigh any possible benefit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Category X medications have demonstrated clear evidence of causing fetal abnormalities and are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy or when pregnancy is possible","The Australian pregnancy medication categories (A, B1-3, C, D, X) help guide prescribing decisions based on safety data"],"references":["Australian Government. Australian categorisation system for prescribing medicines in pregnancy. tga.gov.au. Available from: https://www.tga.gov.au/australian-categorisation-system-prescribing-medicines-pregnancy","B\u00e1nhidy F, Lowry RB, Czeizel AE. Risk and benefit of drug use during pregnancy. Int J Med Sci. 2005;2(3):100-6. doi: 10.7150/ijms.2.100. Epub 2005 Jul 1. PMID: 16007261; PMCID: PMC1168874","Australian Government. Prescribing medicines in pregnancy database tga.gov.au. Available from: https://www.tga.gov.au/products/medicines/find-information-about-medicine/prescribing-medicines-pregnancy-database"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49144"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16053"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49144"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T11:20:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T11:21:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8744"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","